column168: Description Of Events

DRIVER WAS MOVING LOADING ARM FROM COMPARTMENT #3 AT TOP LOADING FACILITY AND CORD FROM LOADNG ARM GOT TANGLED ON TANKER, CAUSING APPROXIMATELY A 20 GALLONS SPILL ON TANKER AND LOADING AREA.  SPILL PADS WERE USED TO CLEAN-UP LOADING AREA AND A FIRE TRUCK WAS BROUGHT AROUND TO WASH OFF TRUCK AND LOT TO SEPERATOR PIT.  SPIL PADS USED TO ABSORB FUEL OUT OF SEPERATOR PIT, AND ALL PADS WERE PUT INTO A DOT DRUM AND WILL BE CARRIED AWAY AS HAZMAT BY AN OUTSIDE HAULER.
NO REMARKS

DRIVER FAILED TO CHECK DOME LID AFTER IT HAD BEEN LOADED BY AN OPERATOR AT THE PLANT.  WHEN DRIVER LEFT THE PLANT APPROXIMATELY 5 TO 10 GALLONS SPILLED OUT OF THE DOME LID.  AREA CLEANED BY MCKENZIE PERSONNEL.

DRIVER MADE A DELIVERY AT THIS ADDRESS.  AFTER MAKING DELIVERY AND UNHOOKING NOZZLE FROM FILL A COUPLE OF DROPS OF OIL CAME FROM TANKS VENT LINE.  THE DRIVER THOUGHT THIS WAS DUE TO BACK PRESSURE FORM UNDER GROUND TANK.  LATER IN THE DAY THE CUSTOMER CALLED MAREX.  TO REPORT OIL RELEASED IN BASEMENT.  MAREX RESPONSED TO CLEAN UP SPILLED OIL.  MAREX REPAIR MAN NOTICED BROKEN GAUGE ON TANK WHERE OIL HAD SPILLED OUT.  REPAIR PERSONE CLEANED UP SPILLED OIL.  MAREX REPAIR MAN NOTICED BROKEN GAUGE ON TANK WHERE OIL HAD SPILLED OUT.  REPAIR PERSON CLEANED UP SPILLED OIL, REPLACED GAUGE AND CLEANED OUT OIL TANKS VENT LINE OF DEBRIS.

SHIPMENT SHRINK WRAPPED IN CONTAINER GROUPS 3 WIDE AND 3 DEEP BUT NOT SECURE TO SKID.  MOTION REVEALED TOP-HEAVY NATURE AND INADEQUACY OF BLOCKING (OF SKIDS).  WHEN GROUP/STACK TOPPLED ONTO SIDE, SOME CONTAINERS WERE NEARLY UPSIDE DOWN.  VENT CAPS SUCCUMBED TO PRESSURE OF LIQUID AND UNSEATED ON SEVERAL CONTAINERS; COMPLETELY DISLODGED FROM ONE AND ALLOWED WEEPING AROUND VENT ON SIX CONTAINERS.  LEAKAGE (FROM TRAILER) INITIALLY CONTAINED BY CATCHING IN AN AVAILABLE DRUM BUT AS LEAKING STARTED AT OTHER POINTS FROM TRAILER, THE ROLLA FIRE DEPT WAS NOTIFIED.  SPILL NEUTRALIZED WITH LIME AND CONTAINERS WASHED/DRIED/RELOADED. NEUTRALIZED SPILL LANDFILLED AFTER COORDINATION WITH NO D.N.R.  SHIPPER NOTIFIED OF INADEQUATE SECURITY ON SKID AND CARRIER TERMINAL THAT LOADED SHIPMENT NOTIFIED TO BRIEF SUPERVISOR AND LOADING CREW OF INCIDENT--VIOLATION OF BLOCKING AND BRACING RULES.

column168: EMPLOYEE UNLOADING SHIPMENT OF TWENTY PAILS WHEN HE NOTICED AN ACCUMULATION OF LIQUID ON TOP OF ONE PAIL.  ACCUMULATION WAS CAUSED BY PRESSURE ON PAIL CAUSING LIQUID TO LEAK OUT OF FAULTY SPOUT ON TOP OF PAIL.  THE ONE PAIL WAS HELD AT MMT FOR DISPOSTION WHILE THE BALANCE OF THE SHIPMENT WAS SENT TO THE CONSIGNEE. THE LEAKING PAIL WAS PLACED IN OS& D WHERE THE TOP WAS TIGHTENED UP.  THE PAIL WAS THEN SENT OT THE CONSIGNEE.

WHILE UNLOADING AT CONSIGNEE'S DRIVER NOTED SPILLAGE ON THE FLOOR OF THE UNIT.  EXAMINATION REVEALED A DRUM LEAKING ABOUT HALF WAY UP THE CONTAINER.  THE DRUM WAS THREE ROWS UP IN THE TRAILER, NEAR THE CENTER. THE DRUMS WERE ON CARDBOARD.  PER THE SHIPPER AND CHEMTREC KITTY LITTER WAS USED TO ABSORB THE RESIN & THE TAILER WAS RETURNED TO THE HOME TERMINAL, AND ALLOWED TO AIR OUT.  SEE ATTACHED SKETCH SUBMITTED BY DRIVER.  RESIN HAD EVAPORATED, AND THE PRODUCT WAS LEFT AT CONSIGNEES.
APPARENTLY ONE CARTON CONTAINING TWO ONE GALLON PAILS WAS DAMAGED BY OTHER REIGHT WHILE IN TRANSIT.  PROPER BLOCKING AND BRACING PROCEDURES WILL BE STRESSED AT THE LOADING FACILITY.
PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING IN UNLOAD.  ONE OF FOUR 1 GALLON CONTAINERS HAD LOOSE CAP.  DAMAGED CARTON WAS DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING HAZMAT DISPOSAL PROCEDURES.

DRIVER/SALESMAN WAS ATTEMPTING TO LOAD A SKID BEHIND THE SKID CONTAINING THE PAILS OF CORROSIVE. HE PUSHED THE SKID TOO TIGHT AGAINST THE OTHER SKID,DAMAGING (1) OF THE PAILS, CAUSING THE SPILL. DRIVER CONTACTED MYSELF AND ADVISED OF THE SITUATION. I CONTACTED CHEMTREC ALONG WITH VIC PRINCE, REGION SAFETY SUPERVISOR, FOR CLEANUP AND DISPOSAL INSTRUCTIONS. THE MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP PER INSTRUCTIONS. AND PLACED IN RECOVERY DRUM AWAITING FUTHER DISPOSAL INSTRUCTIONS. column168: AWE DRIVERS WAS ENROUTE TO PRUDHOE BAY WITH 9246 GALLONS METHANOL. WEATHER CONDITIONS WERE MODERATE 25 DEGREE f. DRIVER WAS CLIMBING HILL, APPROX 3/4 UP THE HILL HE SPIN OUT. REQUIRING HIM TO CHAIN UP. AS THE DRIVE CLIMBED OUT OF THE TRUCK (WITH THE BRAKES SET) THE UNIT STARTED SLIDING BACKWARDS DOWN THE HILL, DUE TO THE ICEY ROAD CONDITIONS. THE TRAILER SLID INTO A DITCH ALONG THE EDGE OF THE ROAD AND GENTLY STOPPED AT A 45 DEGREE ANGLE. A VERY MINOR LEAK DEVELOPED AT THE DOME. THE DDRIVER CONTAINED ALL PRODUCT WITH VEHICLE AND TRAILER MOUNTED SPILL KITS. 1-2 GALLONS OF METHANOL REACHED THE SNOW CONTAMINATED SNOW WAS REMOVED AND RETURNED TO AWE FOR RECYCLING. NO FUTHER CLEANUP ACTIONS REQUIRED.

column168: DR. STATES THAT HE REPORTED TO HOECHST CELANESE TO BE LOADED. WHILE UNIT WAS ON WEIGH SCALES 30 TO 45 MIN. DRIVER REPORTED TO DR'S ROOM TO WAIT ON PAPERWORK. HE WAS ADVISED BY HOECHST PERSONNEL THAT HE WAS READY TO BE LOADED. HE WAS GIVEN THE TRAILER INSP. AND BILL OF LADING AND WAS DIRECTED TO THE LOADING HEADER. DRIVER FAILED TO CHECK BEHIND HOECHST PERSONNEL TO MAKE SURE ALL VALVES WERE CLOSE. WHEN LOAD PROCESS BEGAN PRODUCT RAN OUT OF TRAILER UNLOADING LINE. INTERNAL VALVE WAS CLOSE, PRODUCT FLOW WAS STOPPED AFTER APPROX. 100 GAL PRODUCT SPILLED INTO CONTAINMENT AREA. IMMEDIATELY AFTER INCIDENT BOB RUSSELL, MGR. HOECHST CONDUCTED INVESTIGATION. HE STATED TO DRIVER THAT HOECHSTY PERSONNEL HAD FORGOT AND DID NOT PERFORM THE REQUIRED VACUUM TEST ON TRAILER WHEN IT ENTERED PLANT. THE PRODUCT SPILL WAS DILUTED WITH WATER AND WAS LOADED ONTO ANOTHER TRAILER. IN FUTURE DRIVER WILL CHECK AFTER ALL PERSONNEL TO MAKE SURE ALL VALVES ARE CLOSED AND TANK READY FOR LOADING.
WHEN DRIVER WAS CARRYING HOSE HANDLE HIT A FENCE AND HANDLE OPENED SPRAYING ABOUT 1 GALLON OF OIL ON FENCE. OIL WAS CLEANED UP NO DAMAGE TO PROPERTY.

1EHICLE WAS ENTERING CUSTOMER DRIVEWAY, AND DRIVER CUT TOO CLOSE TO GATE. TRAILER STRUCK THE GATE AND DAMAGED THE 1ST & 2ND MANIFOLDS, IN ADDITION TO SCRATCHING THE TANKERS' SIDE.  THE GATE FELL ON A VEHICLE PARKED NEXT TO THE GATE.  APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL DRAINED FROM THE #1 MANIFOLD.  #2 MAINIFOLD WAS DAMAGED, BUT THERE WAS NO FUEL IN THE #2 COMPARTMENT.

column168: A CARTON OF FLAMMABLE LIQUID (DEVELOPER) OUT OF 3M WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING ON ARRIVAL AT PRESTON'S NORFOLK, VIRGINIA SERVICE CENTER.  CARTON WAS DAMAGED BY OTHER FREIGHT SHIFTING.  THE DAMAGED BOTTLE WAS RESEALED AND THE DAMAGED CARTON WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER FOR CREDIT AND INSPECTION.

AMAX WAS CONTACTED BY THE NORFOLK SOUTHERN R.R. AT ABOUT 7 PM ON SAT. JAN. 2ND AND ADVISED THAT AN EMPTY TANK CAR WHICH AHD BEEN RELEASED WAS IN THE NORFOLK SOUTHERN YARD IN NEW ORLENAS AND THAT AN ODOR WAS DETECTED FROM THE CAR.  AMAX RESPONDED TO THE CALL FROM THE RAILROAD AND DISPATCHED PAUL PRITCHARD, ONE SAFETY SUPERVISOR AND TWO (2) OPERATIONS SUPERVISORS (EQUIPPED WITH BREATHING APPARATUS, GASKETS, AND TOOLS). ON ARRIVAL AT THE SCENE, THE NEW ORLEANS FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS ALREADY PRESENT AND A REPRESENTATIVE FROM THE BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES (ASSO. OF AMERICAN RAILROADS) WAS ON HAD ALREADY ENROUTE.  AMAX PERSONNEL WERE ABLE TO STOP THE LEAK BY CHANGEING OUT A GASKET ON THE 2" LIQUID VALVE.  NO EVACUATION WAS NEEDED SINCE THE RAIL YARD IS MOSTLY AN INDUSTRIAL AREA AND THE LEAK WAS VERY MINOR (YOU HAD TO GET NEXT OT THE CAR TO SMELL IT). MONTANA SULPHUR & CHEMICAL CO. WAS CONTACTED JAN. 4, 1993 ABOUT THIS INCIDENT, GATX 15816 IS INROUTE TO MONTANA SULPHUR & CHEMICAL CO.  AND WILL BE THOROUGHLY INSPECTED BEFORE RE-LOADING.

DRUM WAS SETTING ON DOCK, INTERLINE CARRIER CAME TO THE DOCK AND DELIVERED TWO SKIDS TO ABF.  IT WAS NOTICED RIGHT AFTER HE LEFT, THAT A PUDDLE WAS FORMING ON THE DOCK.  WHEN INSPECTED, A PUNCTURE HOLE WAS FOUND IN THE DRUM ABOUT 1 FOOT UP FOOT UP FROM THE BOTTOM. THE DRUM WAS QUICKLY PUT ON ITS SIDE, SAFETY WAS CALLED, AND CLEANUP STARTED WITH DRY FLOOR.

THE SPILL WAS ALSO REPORTED TO THE VIRGINIA STATE WATER CONTROL BOARD.

VEHICLE HAD JUST LEFT THE CO YARD AND WAS PROCEEDING OUT TOWARDS THE MAIN ROAD, WHEN TRAILER CAME UNCOUPLED FROM THE FIFTH WHEEL OF THE TRACTOR. THE PROBABLE CAUSE OF COUPLING, FAILURE WAS THE ADVERSE WEATHER CONDITIONS AND EXTREMELY COLD, SHILL FACTOR OF -42 DEGREES.  FAILURE TO COUPLE PROPERLY, WAS ATTRIBUTED TO THE STIFFNESS OF THE GREASE IN THE LATCHING MECHANISM OF THE FIFTH WHEEL. ACTION TAKEN TO PREVENT SIMILAR INCIDENTS IN THE FUTURE, HAS BEEN RECOMMENDED THAT THE FIFTH WHEELS BE CLEANED ON ALL TRACTORS AND THE LUBRICANTS BE REPLACED WITH A CLEAN AND LIGHTER TYPE OF LUBRICANT FOR THE WINTER MONTHS.

column168: DRIVER WAS HEADING WEST BOUND ON WI HYW 54.  IT WAS SNOWING AND THE ROAD WAS COVERED WITH SNOW, NO CENTER LINE VISIBLE.  VEHICLE SPEED WAS 30-35 MPH.  (DRIVERS REPORT)  I SAW A SNOW PLOW COMING TOWARD ME FROM THE WEST. HE WAS PLOWING SHOULDER SO HE AND I COULD PASS WITHOUT HITTING.  THE PLOW APPEARED OVER THE CENTER LINE, BUT SNOW MADE IT IMPOSSIBLE TO TELL WHERE I WAS GOING, I GET OFF THE SHOULDER AND WAS UNABLE TO BRING THE TRACTOR BACK ON THE RAOD.  THE MOMENTUM OF THE LOAD KEPT ME GOING STRAIGHT AHEAD DOWN THE DITCH EMBANKMENT WHERE THE UNIT OVERTURNED. THE DRIVER FOUND A HAMMER AND WITH THE SAFETY EQUIPMENT ON, DROVE A PINE BRANCH INTO THE HOLE WHERE THE RUPTURE DISK ONCE WAS SLOWING THE LEAK.  A BUCKET WAS ALSO USED TO CATCH LIQUID.

column168: RECEIVED CALL FROM MN HWY PATROL AT APPROX. 11:30 AM REPORTING UNIT ROLLED OVER 10 MILES SOUTH OF EVELETH, GAS LEAKING FROM FRONT COMPARTMENT.  FIRE DEPT WAS ALREADY ON SCENE, NORTHBOUND TRAFFIC DIVERTED TO SOUTHBOUND SIDE OF 4 LANE HWY TO PROTECT SCENE.  CONTACTED MN PCA AND NATIONAL RESPONSE CNTR.  CONTRACTED OSI TO PERFORM PRODUCT TRANSFER TO ANOTHER UNIT DISPATCHED TO SCENE AND WRECKER SERVICE TO UPRIGHT UNIT AND REMOVE IT FROM SCENE UPON COMPLETION OF PRODUCT TRANSFER.  COMPLETED AT APPROX. 6:00PM THAT EVENING. DRIVER REPORTED THAT HE PULLED UNIT ONTO SHOULDER TO INVESTIGATE A BANGING SOUND COMING FROM THE TRAILER.  SNOW PLOWS HAD PUSHED SNOW BANK FROM SHULDER, BUT ON GRADE WITH SHOULDER.  RIGHT SIDE OF UNIT ON COMPACTED SNOW WHEN UNIT CAME TO FULL STOP.  SNOW GAVE WAY AND UNIT ROLLED OVER INTO DITCH.  THE PRESSURE OFTHE PRODUCT AGAINST FRONT DOME CAUSED THE DOME COVER TO PUSH OPEN SLIGHTLY AND STARTED LEAKING.  FIRE DEPT WAS ABLE TO SLOW LEAKAGE UPON ARRIVAL.  APPROXIMATELY 190 GAL WAS SPILLED FROM THE FRONT COMPARTMENT CONTAINING 4000 GALS.  TRAILER ROLLED ONTO RIGHT FRONT CORNER FIRST, NO OHTER COMPARTMENTS LEAKED ANY PRODUCT. CONTRACTED WITH OSI TO PERFORM SITE REMEDIATION THE FOLLOWING DAY AND COORDINATED CLEAN UP WITH DULUTH OFFIC OF MN PCA.  INCIDENT HAS BEEN HANDLED TO SATISFACTION OF ALL AUTHORITIES INVOLVED UNITL FINAL INSPECTION CAN BE PERFORMED AFTER SNOW IS MELTED.  *CONTINUED ON ATTACHMENT*

column168: THIS CAR WAS 1 OF A CUT OF 4 CARS, MOVED AROSS THE BORDER INTO THE INTERNATIONAL BORDER EXCHANGE TRACKS 1/8/93.  WITHIN AN HOUR, WE REALIZED THESE CARS WERE PRESSURE CARS, WITH NO DOCUMENTATION, NO PLACARDS, AND NO STENSILING.  WE CONTACTED THE MEXICAN RAILWAY TO COME GET THEM, AS THEY WERE BEING REJECTED FOR NOT COMPLYING WITH D.O.T. REGULATIONS.  WE WERE ADVISED THAT DUE TO THE FLOODING CONDITIONS WHICH WERE OCCURRING IN MEXICO AT THE TIME, THEIR LOCOMOTIVES WERE CUT OFF FROM NOGALES UNTIL SOMETIME LATE 1/9/93.  AT 0800HRS. 1/9/93, WE WERE NOTIFIED THAT A CITIZEN HAD COMPLAINED OF AN ODOR EMITTING FROM THE RAILYARD.  THE NOGALES, AZ. FIRE DEPT. INVESTIGATED, AND BEING UNABLE TO DETERMINE THE CONTENTS OR PREVIOUS CONTENTS, EVACUATED THE IMMEDIATE AREA AROUND THE CARS.  THEY THEN ORDERED US TO SHOVE THEM BACK INTO MEXICO.  WE RESISTED THIS AS IT WOULD ONLY MOVE THE PROBLEM FROM ONE AREA TO ANOTHER, AND THE MEXICAN POLICE SAID THEY WOULD ARREST THE TRAIN CREW IF THEY MOVED THE CARS INTO MEXICO (THIS IS REQUIRED TO BE DONE BY THE MEXICAN RAILROAD).  THE FIRE DEPT. THEN REQUIRED THAT THE CARS BE TAKEN OUTSIDE TOWN TO A LESS POPULATED AREA. THE AGREEMENTS IN PLACE STATE THAT THIS WOULD ENTAIL ACCEPTANCE OF THE CARS AT INTERNATIONAL ENTERCHANGE.  WE CONTACTED THE MEXICAN BROKERAGE, AND THE MEXICAN RAILROAD AND U.S. CUSTOMS TO ADVISE THEM THIS WAS STRICTLY TO PROTECT BOTH THE MEXICAN AND AMERICAN POPULATION.  WE THEN MOVED THEM OUTSIDE WON TO A MORE ISOLATED AREA. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT EACH OF THE CARS WERE IN FACT EMITTING AN ODOR THAT, THROUGH PREVIOUS EXPERIENCE WAS IDENTIFIED AS ANHYDROUS AMMONIA. IT WAS APPARENT THAT THE CARS WERE RESIDUE ANHYDROUS AMMONIA CARS, ALTHOUGH NO DOCUMENTATION HAD BEEN PRESENTED TO BEAR THIS OUT, AND IN FACT ONE OF THE CARS (UTLX 83250) WAS STENSILED PROPANE GAS-LIQUIDED. NONE OF THE CARS HAD ANY PLACARDS AT ALL.  UPON OPENING THE "DOMES" IT WAS DISCOVER THAT NONE OF THE 2" VALVE PLUGS IN ANY OFTHE 4 CARS HAD BEEN PLACED IN THE VALVES (1 OF THE 1" PLUGS WAS COMPLETELY MISSING), AND NONE OF THE 1/4" PLUGS IN THE SAMPLE VALVE OR THE GUAGING DEVICE HAD BEEN INSTALLED. UTLX 83738 AND UTLX 83251 EACH HAD THE LIQUID VALVE HANDLE UP AT A 45 DEGREE ANGLE, BUT WERE NOT LEAKING LIQUID, ONLY SMELL. UTLX 83742 AND UTLX 83250 HAD AN APPARENT HISS COMING FROM THE PACKING GLAND NUT ON THE GUAGING DEVICE. ALL CARS WERE SECURED AGAINST LEAKAGE, PLUG REPLACED AND REINSTALLED, EVERYTHING WAS TIGHTENED AND SECURED FOR TRANSPORTATION. THE CARS WERE THEN TAKEN BACK TO THE INTERNATIONAL BORDER INTERCHANGE TRACK AND THE MEXICAN RAILROAD TOOK THEM BACK ACROSS THE BORDER AT 1700 HRS TO BE BROUGHT INTO COMPLIANCE WITH DOT REGULATIONS.  tHE CITIZEN WHICH FIRST COMPLAINED OF AN ODOR, REFUSED ANY TREATMENT BY NOGALES FIRE DEPT. AND WE HAVE BEEN UNABLE TO OBTAIN THE NAME OF THE INDIVIDUAL.

THE DRIVER WAS WRITTEN UP AND COUNSELED ON THE PROPER PROCEDURE OF PULLING SKIDS AWAY FROM THE FRT LOADED IN FRONT OF THEM WITH ONLY APRT OF THE FORK BLADES BEFORE MOVING THE SKID WIHT THE FULL LENGTH OF THE BLADES.  HE REALIZED THIS WILL AVOID SIMILAR FUTURE PUNCTURES AND ASSURES THIS WILL NOT HAPPEN AGAIN.

column62: Fire, Temperature, or Heat; Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: VEHICLE #1 (CARGO TANK), #2 AND #3 WERE ALL NORTHBOUND ON I94.  VEHICLE #2 PASSES VEHICLE #3 IN THE RIGHT-HAND EMERGENCY PARKING LANE.  THE DRIVER OF VEHICLE #2 LOST CONTROL OF HIS VEHICLE, CAME BACK ONTO THE ROADWAY SPINNING.  VEHICLE #2 DID A 360 DEGREE TURN AND A 180 DEGREE TURN, IT WAS THEN FACING SOUTHBOUND IN THE CENTER NORTHBOUND LANE.  VEHICLE #1 STRUCK VEHICLE #2 CAUSING VEHICLE #2 TO ENTER THE PATH OF VEHICLE #3 WHICH WAS IN THE RIGHT HAND NORTHBOUND LANE.  VEHICLE #3 STRUCK VEHICLE #2, AFTER BEING STRUCK VEHI CLE #2 SPUN 180 DEGREES AND CAME TO REST IN THE RIGHT HAND EMERGENCY STOPPING LANE FACING NORTH.  AFTER STRIKING VEHICLE #2, VEHICLE #1 JACKKNIFED AND STARTED TO SLIDE ACROSS THE RIGHT HAND LANE.  AFTER STRIKING VEHICLE #2. VEHICLE #3 WENT ONTO THE EMERGENCY STOPPING LANE AND TRAVELED ALONG THE GUARDRAIL SEPARATING THE ROADWAY FROM A STEEP EMBANKMENT.  AS VEHICLE #3 TRAVELED ALONG THE GUARDRAIL VEHICLE #1 STRUCK A SNOWMOBILE TRAILER BEING TOWED BY VEHICLE #3.  THE SNOWMOBILE TRAILER SEPARATED FRON VEHICLE #3 AS VEHICLE #1 BROKE THRU THE GUARDRAIL, VEHICLE #3 CONTINUED NORTH FOR A SAFE DISTANCE.  AFTER BREAKING THRU THE GUARDRAIL VEHICLE #1 TRAVELED DOWN THE EMBANKMENT BURSTING INTO FLAMES.  AS VEHICLE #1 REACHED THE BOTTOM OF THE EMBANKMENT IT ROLLED ONTO ITS' TOP.  UPON ROLLING OVER, VEHICLE #1 BROKE APART.  TRAILER FROM TRACTOR AND TRACTOR CAB FROM TRACTOR FRAME FATALLY INJURING THE DRIVER.  VEHICLE #1 CAME TO REST WITH THE TRAILER AND TRACTOR FRAME IN THE DITCH OF THE EAST FRONTAGE ROAD. THE TRAILER FRONT WAS FACING SOUTH, NORTH TO THE TRACTOR FRAME.  THE TRACTOR FRAME FRONT WAS FACING NORTH, SOUTH OF THE TRAILER.  THE TRACTOR CAB WAS UPRIGHT IN THE CENTER OF THE FRONTAGE ROAD 51 FEET EAST OF THE TRACTOR FRAME.  THE FRONT OF THE TRACTOR CAB WAS FACING SOUTH.  THE DECEASED DRIVER OF VEHICLE WAS FOUND IMMEDIATELY SOUTH OF THE TRACTOR CAB. THE SNOWMOBILE TRAILER CAME TO REST SOUTH AND WEST OF THE TRACTOR FRAME ON THE EMBANKMENT.  THE DRIVER OF VEHICLE #2 RECEIVED BURNS TO HIS FACE IN AN ATTEMPT TO AID THE DRIVER OF VEHICLE #1.  REPORTS INDICATE THAT BLOOD WAS TO BE DRAWN FROM THE DECEASED DRIVER OF VEHICLE #1 AND SUBMITTED FOR SUBSTANCE ABUSE TESTING.  RESULTS ARE UNKNOWN.  FIRST RESPONDING FIRE UNITS CONTROLLED THE NOTIFICATION OF THE FOLLOWING AGENCIES.  RACINE COUNTY EMERGENCY GOVERNMENT, WISCONSIN DEPARTMENT OF NATURAL RESOURCES AND E & K HAZARDOUS WASTE SERVICES, INC. WERE CONTACTED.  DUE TO THE SIZE OF THE FIRE 194 NORTH AND SOUTH BOUND WERE CLOSED FROM CTH K TO STH 11.  STH 20 WAS CLOSED EAST AND WESTBOUND FROM THE WEST FRONTAGE ROAD EAST TO CTH V. BECAUSE OF STORM SEWERS BEING CONTAMINATED, SEVERAL NEARBY BUSINESSES WERE ALSO EVACUATED.  THEY WERE COLONY INN RESTAURANT, BURGER KING AND MCDONALDS.  A NEARBY GAS STATION ALSO WAS ADVISED TO SHUT DOWN THERE PUMPS.  ACCORDING TO REPORTS RECIEVED, APPROXIMATELY 20-30 GALLONS OF THE FLAMMABLE LIQUID WAS RECOVERED FROM A DRAINAGE DITCH.  THE REPORT FURTHER STATES THAT NO FURTHER
FREIGHT SHIFTED DURING TRANSIT RIPPING OPEN ONE BAG AND ABOUT 8 OUNCES SPILLED. CONTAMINATED MATERIAL IS HELD AWAITING DISPOSITION.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Abrasion; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: WHEN THE RESIN WAS LOADED THE TRUCK HAD A 40'X36" D.A. PIPE DOWN THE MIDDLE TO THE FLAT BED. THE PIPE WAS BLOCKED AND TIED DOWN PROPERLY, BUT THE SHIPPER PLACED THE DRUM'S UP TIGHT AGAINST THE PIPE. THE DRIVER ALSO FAILED TO BLOCK THE INSIDE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM'S TO KEEP THEM AWAY FROM THE PIPE. AT APPROXIMATELY 1400 HRS. ON JAN 28TH 1993 THE DRIVER PULLED OVER TO CHECK HIS LOAD AT BLACK BUTE SUMMIT ON I-5 AND AT THAT TIME HE NOTICED RESIN WAS OOZING FROM 3 DRUMS AT THE REAR OF THE LOAD AT THE POINT ON THE SIDE OF THE DRUM THAT WAS TOUCHING THE PIPE. A CHP OFFICER ARRIVED ON THE SCENE WHO CONTACTED MYSELF AND INSTRUCTED ME TO FIND A TEAM OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL HANDLER'S LICENSED BY THE STATE OF CALIFORNIA TO COME AND OVERPAK THE 3 LEAKING DRUMS. I CONTACTED A/C INDUSTRIALS SERVICES CORP IN CHINO, CALIFORNIA. THEY ARRIVED AT 2130 HRS. AND COMPLETED THEIR JOB OF OVERPACKING THE 3 DRUMS AND CLEAN UP OF MATERIAL ON THE DECK OF THE TRAILER BY 2300 HRS. TO PREVENT FURTHER INCIDENTS OF THIS NATURE I HAVE GIVEN SPECIAL INSTRUCTION AT OUR LAST SAFETY MEETING CONCERNING LOADING, BLOCKING AND SECURING OF BARRELS WHEN BEING LOADED WITH OTHER FREIGHT. THE ONE RECOMMENDATION I CAN MAKE IS FOR SHIPPERS TO MAKE SURE THE DRUMS NOT BE LOADED IN SUCH A WAY THAT THEY TOUCH OTHER FREIGHT IN A FASHION WHERE THE TWO PIECES WILL RUB HOLES IN EACH OTHER.

THE DRIVER PICKED UP THE LOADED MC307 S/S TRAILER AT NALCO, HEPZIBAH, WV AT APPROXIMATELY 2100 HRS. TO DELIVER THE LOAD TO CORBIN, KY. THE DRIVER WENT APPROXIMATELY TWO TO THREE MILES AND SAW SOME OF THE PRODUCT WAS COMING FROM THE DOME LID OF THE VESSEL. THE DRIVER STOPPED AND SECURED THE DOME LID AND THEN DROVE TO A SERVICE STATION AND REPORTED THE SPILL TO MOUNTAINEER BULK SERVICE'S INC. HE THEN REPORTED THE SPILL TO THE HARRISON COUNTY SHERIFF'S DEPT.,WHO IN TURN NOTIFIED THE WV DEPT. OF NATURAL RESOURCES AND THE DEPT OF HIGHWAYS. AS IN THE PAST THE DRIVERS WERE AGAIN NOTIFIED TO PRE-TRIP THEIR EQUIPMENT AND TO MAKE CERTAIN  THAT ALL OPENINGS, VALVES,ETC. WERE SECURE AND SAFE BEFORE MOVING THEIR EQUIPMENT. THIS INCIDENT IS BEING REVIEWED AS TO WHAT ACTION TO TAKE ON THE DRIVER.

column168: WHEN AIRCRAFT PALLET P6PT312FT WAS UNLOADED FROM AIRCRAFT N636FE ON ARRIVAL SYD IT WAS FOUND THAT MANY PACKAGES OF THIS SHPT AND SOME CARTONS OF OTHER SHIPMENTS WERE COVERED WITH A BROWN LIQUID, OR PARTLY COVERED. THE AIRCRAFT WAS CHECKED FOR ANY SPILLAGE AROUND THE POSITION OF THE PALLET DURING THE FLT.  NO SIGNS OF SPILLAGE THERE.  MANY OF THE PLASTIC CANS HAD MINOR LEAKAGES THROUGH THE LIDS - WHEN THE CONTAINERS WERE SHAKEN THE LIDS STARTED LEAKING.  TWO CONTAINERS WERE LATER FOUND TO HAVE SPLIT IN THE UPPER PARTS AND TO HAVE LOST APPROX. 1/3 OF THE CONTENTS EACH.

PACKAGE WAS INSPECTED DUE TO SMELL.  INSPECTION DETERMINED LEAKAGE WAS ON SEAM ON SIDE OF PLASTIC CONTAINER.  THE SEAM APPPEARED TO FAIL OR BE DEFECTIVE.  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND WAS VERY CONCERNED AND ASKED THAT THE SHIPMENT WAS VERY CONCERNED AND ASKED THAT THE SHIPMENT BE RETURNED IN A RECOVERY DRUM FOR FURTHER INVESTIGATION.
PACKAGE FELL FROM PD -1 SLID.  BURST OPEN.  ENTIRE CONTENTS DISPOSED OF USING U.P.S. HAZMAT DISPOSAL PROCEDURE.

column168: DRIVER INTERRUPTED DELIVERY INTO THE REGULAR TANK TO RESTICK, HE DISCONNECTED THE DROP, BUT LEFT THE MALE END CONNECTED.  HE CHECKED THE STICK READINGS OF ANOTHER PRODUCT'S TANK ALSO AND THEN RESUMED DELIVERY INTO THE REGULAR GASOLINE TANK.  HE FORGOT THAT HE HAD DISCONNECTED FROM THE REGULAR TANK.  HE REALIZED HIS ERROR AND SHUTDOWN THE DISCHARGE OF PRODUCT.  THE GASOLINE WAS PICKED UP WITH SORBENT PADS AND OIL DRY AND HE NOTIFIED THE TERMINAL MANAGER WHO RESPONDED WITH OTHER TERMINAL PERSONNEL TO INVESTIGATE THE INCIDENT AND TO MAKE SURE CLEANUP WAS SUFFICIENT.  ALL WASTE MATERIALS WERE RETURNED TO THE TERMINAL FOR SPILL CONTRACTOR, WEAVERTOWN ENVIRONMENTAL TO TRANSPORT AND DISPOSE OF.  SHOWED "SPILL" VIDEO IN SAFETY MEEDTING, TO INCREASE AWARENESS AND PREVENTIVE.

A FULL-TIME SUPERVISOR WAS NOTIFIED IMMEDIATELY AND THE AREA WAS CLEARED.  I WAS ABLE TO NEUTRALIZE THE MATERIAL WITH SODIUM BICARBONATE.  THE PACKAGE WAS APPARENTLY DROPPED BECAUSE THE BOTTOM OF THE BOTTLE BURST OPEN.  LOADERS NEED TO MAKE SURE THEY USE PROPER PACKAGE HANDLING.  THERE WAS ENOUGH INTERNAL CUSHIONING ON THE INSIDE.

column168: DURING SWITCHING OPERATION THE SWITCH CREW DISCOVERED UTLX 794, LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE FROM THE COMPARTMENT CONTAING THE METHYL ETHYL KETONE.  CAR WAS ISOLATED AND A CP HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RESPONSE COORDINATOR WAS CALLED TO INSPECT THE CAR.  THE CAR WAS FOUND TO HAVE A DEFECTIVE GASKET BETWEEN THE TANK SHELL AND BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WHICH COULD NOT BE REPAIRED IN THE FIELD UNDER LOAD.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED, WHO ARRANGE FOR TWO TANKS TRUCKS AND O.H. MATERIALS TO TRANSFER THE METHYL ETHYL KETONE INTO THE TANKS TRUCKS.  THE METHYL ETHYL KETONE WAS TRUCKED TO ITS BILLED DESTINATION, AND THE ISOPROPANOL WAS ALLOWED TO CONTINUE ON TO BILLED DESTINATION ON THE TANK CAR.  NO CLEAN UP WAS NECESSARY IN CONNECTION WITH THIS INCIDENT.

PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED IN BIN ON SKYLINE CENTER.  CAP WAS LOOSE ON 2.18 LITER BOTTLE OF DEVELOPER REPLENISHER.  THE COMPLETE PACKAGE WAS REPACKED AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  DAMAGED CARTON WAS DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DISPOSAL PROCEDURES.

PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED IN BIN ON SKYLINE CENTER.  CAP WAS LOOSE ON 1 GALLON CONTAINER.  THE COMPLETE PACKAGE WAS REPACKED AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  DAMAGED CARTON WAS DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DISPOSAL PROCEDURES.

THE TRUCK WAS BEING UNLOADED AND WHEN A STACK WAS FILLED. A DRUM OFF THE REAR STACK FELL AND POPPED ITS LID. THE LIQUID WAS DRIED WITH OH DRY AND PACKED UP WITH SPILL PADS. ALL MATERIAL WAS RECOVERED.  TO PREVENT REOCCURANCE SHIPPER WAS INSTRUCTED TO IMPROVE THEIR STRAPPING OF LOAD PER SHIPMENT.

column168: LOADING CRUDE OIL AT COLDWATER E-TK-1.  OVERFILLED TRAILER, SPILLING CRUDE OIL OUT OF VENT HOSE.

DRIVER ARRIVED AT PERRY PIPELINE STATION WITH A LOAD OF CRUDE OIL TO OFF LOAD.  HE OPENED ALL VALVES ON THE STATION PIPING AND MISTAKENLY PUT HIS PUMP INTO THE LOAD POSITION RATHER THAT THE UNLOAD POSITION.  CHECK VALVE IN STATION PIPING FAILED AND THE TANK TRAILER OVERFILLED SPILLING APPROXIMATELY 126 GALLONS.  THE OIL WAS CLEANED UP WITHIN AN HOUR.  CHECK VALVE WAS REPLACED IMMEDIATELY AND ALL OTHER SPILLS.  DRIVER GIVEN STRONG VERBAL REPRIMAND.

column17: CARMAN J A TRUCKING CO INC
column168: VII VIII ABOVE.  NO PACKAGING FAILURE INVOLVED. THIS SPILL WAS THE RESULT OF A TANK OVERFILL.  OUR DRIVER WAS TRANSFERRING #2 OIL FROM ONE TANK ON GOLUB CORP.'S PROPERTY TO ANOTHER TANK ON THEIR PROPERTY.  ON HIS FINAL LOAD, OUR DRIVER MISCALCULATED THE AVAILABLE CAPACITY IN THE TANK HE WAS PUMPING INTO.  AS THE LAST OF THE OIL CAME OFF OUR TRUCK, THE ABOVE GROUND STORAGE TANK OVERFILLED.  THE OIL CAME OUT THE DOME COVER ON THE TANK AND WAS CONTAINED IN THE STEEL DYKE SURROUNDING THE TANK.  THE DYKE HAD AT LEAST TWO FEET OF WATER IN IT WHICH HAD TO BE VACUUMED OFF TO RECOVER THE OIL.  THE NEW YORK STATE DEPT. OF ENVIRONMENTAL CONSERVATION WAS NOTIFIED AND ASSIGNED A REFERENCE # 9211391 TO THE INCIDENT.  THE WATER/OIL MIX WAS TAKEN TO CIBRO PETROLEUM IN ALBANY, N.Y. FOR PROCESSING.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: (A & B)  ON 01-02-93 AT 0624 HOURS, DPS RECEIVED A CALL OF A STRUCTURE (NEAR SOUTH CITY LIMITS.)  LT. EDDY BURKS OF THE NIGHT SHIFT DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE.  LT. BURKS ARRIVED ON SCENE AND REQUESTED MUTUAL AID ASSISTANCE FROM THE VOLUNTEER DEPARTMENTS AND DISPATCHED STATION #4 CLOSEST FIRE HYDRANT PLACEMENT AT HWY 54 SOUTH AND WRIGHT AVENUE.  THE VOLUNTEER DEPARTMENTS HAVE TANKER WATER SUPPLIES TO FEED THE PUMPERS. THE VOLUNTEER DEPARTMENTS WHO RESPONDED WERE DUNGAN, ALAMO WEST, DOG CANYON, AND BOLES ACRES.  LT. BURKS ALSO ACTIVATED MUTUAL AID WITH HOLOMAN AIR FORCE BASE WHO SENT A PUMP AND TOLL FOAM RESCUE TRUCK TO ATTACK.  LT. ANDERSON ARRIVED AND HAD A TANKER SUPPLY ATTACH TO UNIT #30 AND ELEVATED THE REMOVE LADDER NOZZLE FOR AN AERIAL ATTACK.  ALAMO WEST SET UP A DELUGE GUN WITH A FOAM NOZZLE INDUCTOR FOR AN UPWIND ATTACK.  LT. ANDERSON, OFFICER JIM BIRD, OFFICER KERRY JARRETT AND OFFICER MATT FLOTTE SUITED UP WITH BREATHING APPARATUS AND ATTACKED DIRECTLY INTO THE FIRE WITH 1 1/2" USING THE FOAM ATTACHED LINE OFF OF UNIT #30.  THIS EFFORT EXTINGUISHED THE MAJORITY OF THE FIRE EXCEPT FOR INSIDE THE OVERTURNED CAB.  A SECOND ATTACK WITH THE 1 1/2" FOAM LINE EXTINGUISHED THE REMAINDER.  HOLLOMAN'S PUMPER LAID A BLANKET OF FOAM DOWN TO PREVENT REIGNITION.  LT. ANDERSON DIRECTED OFFICER MATT FLOTTS TO PROCEED WITH THE FATAL ACCIDENT INVESTIGATION AND TO WORK WITH NM STATE POLICE OFFICER CHARLIE DEVINE (NMSP HAZARDOUS MATERIALS OFFICER) IN HIS INVESTIGATION.  LT. ANDERSON DIRECTED OFFICER BIRD AND OFFICER JARRETT TO PROCEED WITH EXTRACTION. NORTH 54 AUTO SALVAGE WAS CALLED IN TO ASSIST IN EXTRICATION AND TO REMOVE THE WRECKAGE.  LT. ANDERSON NOTED THE FOLLOWING: THE TRACTOR WAS OVERTURNED AS WERE BOTH TANKER TRAILERS.  THE PUP TRAILER (2ND TRAILER) APPEARED TO HAVE BROKEN LOOSE AND WAS ALONG SIDE AND PARALLEL WITH THE TRACTOR.  THE FIRST TRAILER WAS STILL ATTACHED TO THE 5TH WHEEL AND WAS IN LINE WITH THE TRACTOR.  THE BURNED AREA INCLUDED AN AREA APPROXIMATELY FIFTY FEET (UPWIND) ON THE ASPHALT SOUTH OF THE FINAL RESTING PLACE AND IN A DITCH RUNNING PARALLEL FOR APPROXIMATELY 460' SOUTH WHERE GASOLINE HAD LEAKED AND RUN INTO THE DITCH.  THE TRACTOR WAS A COMPLETE BURN DOWN.  THE TOP HALVES OF THE ALUMINUM TRAILERS WERE LEFT AFTER THE BOTTOMS MELTED. (OVERTURNED).  A BODY WAS LOCATED INSIDE THECAB.  THE TORSO AND BUTTOCKS WERE ON THE DRIVERS SEAT WITH THE UPPER BODY FOLDED TOWARDS THE PASSENGER SIDE (INTERIOR).  THE LOWER LEGS WERE TOWARD THE DOOR.  THE DASH WAS MASHED INTO THE FRONT OF THE DRIVERS SEAT.  THE CAB HAD TO BE CUT APART TO REMOVE THE BODY.  ALAMO WEST SET UP A 1 1/2" ATTACK LINE WITH A TANKER WATER SUPPLY JUST SOUTH OF THE EXTRICATION EFFORTS FOR PROTECTION.  UNIT #30 SETS UP WITH THE REMOTE AERIAL ATTACK NOZZLE DIRECTLY OVER EXTRICATION EFFORTS SUPPLIED BY A WATER TANKER ATTACHED TO A HARD SUCTION, ALSO FOR PROTECTION.  LT. ANDERSON WALKED SOUTH ON US HWY 54 AND NOTED WHERE THE TRUCK HAD LEFT THE ROADWAY, TRAVELING SOME DISTANCE BEF

column168: VEHICLE 1 WAS TRAVELING EASTBOUND ON INTERSTATE 94.  NEAR THE ENTRANCE RAMP ONTO INTERSTATE 94 EB FROM DEARING ROAD, THE TRACTOR VEERED LEFT ONTO THE CONCRETE WALL.  THE TRAILER WENT OVER THE WALL, EVENTUALLY COMING TO REST FACING WESTBOUND.  THE TRACTOR SLID EASTBOUND BEFORE COMING TO REST ON THE DRIVER'S SIDE.  BOTH THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER WERE ENGULFED IN FLAMES AND BURNED DOWN TO THEIR FRAMES.  THE DRIVER WAS KILLED.  HAZARD MATERIALS INCIDENT REPORT 152183 WAS FILED WITH PETTY OFFICER BENNETT, US DOT, ON JANUARY 7, 1993.  THE MICHIGAN DEPARTMENT OF NATURAL RESOURCES WAS NOTIFIED ON JANUARY 7, 1993.  THE PARMA-SANDSTONE TOWNSHIP FIRE DEPARTMENT OF PARMA, MI ASSISTED IN CONTAINING THE ENSUING FIRE AND SPILL.  AFTER THE FIRE WAS EXTINGUISHED, THE REMNANTS OF THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER WERE TOWED BY JIMMIE'S SERVICE TO THEIR FACILITY IN JACKSON, MI.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: AT 0232, HAZ MAT SORT LEAD, RHONDA CLONCH, REPORTED A SHIPMENT THAT WAS GIVINGOFF AN ODOR OF GASOLINE. AT 0234, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR, TONY FRYEAND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SPECIALIST, RANDY WILLIAMS ARRIVED AT THE HAZ MAT SORT.THIS SHIPMENT WAS SITTING OUTSIDE THE SORT BUILDING. THERE WAS A "FLAMMABLELIQUID" LABEL AND A "CARGO AIRCRAFT ONLY" LABEL ON THE SHIPMENT. rANDY wILLIAMSDONED AN ORGANIC VAPOR CARTRIDGE MASK AND STRUCTURAL FIRE FIGHTING GEAR TOINVESTIGATE THE INNER CONTENTS OF THE FIBERBOARD BOX. THERE WERE FOUR  ON-QUARTMETAL RECEPTACLES INSIDE. ONE OF THE FOUR METAL RECEPTACLES. THE CLOSURE WASDAMAGED. THESE WERE SCREW TYPE CLOSURES WITH AN INNER METAL SEAL. THE INNERMETAL SEAL WAS NOT PROPERLY PUT IN. THERE WAS A SMALL HOLE IN IT. THIS WASPROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND PROPER CERTIFICATION DID ACCOMPANY THIS SHIPMENT.THIS SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND FORWARDED ON TO IT'SDESTINATION.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: AT 0145, HAZ MAT SORT SUPERVISOR, TOM ARCHIBALD REPORTED A SHIPMENT THAT WASGIVING OFF A STRONG ODOR OF GAOLINE. AT 0147, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR,TONY FRYE AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SPECIALIST, RANDY WILLIAMS, ARRIVED AT THE HAZ MAT SORT. THE SHIPMENT WAS SITTING OUTSIDE THE BUILDING. THERE WERE SEVEN PIECES IN THE SHIPMENT AND ALL WERE FIBERBOARD BOXES. RANDY WILLIAMS DONED AN ORGANIC VAPOR CARTRIDGE MASK AND STRUCTURAL FIRE FIGHTING GEAR TO INVESTIGATE THE INNER CONTENTS OF EACH OF THE FIBERBOARD BOXES. INSIDE EACH FIBERBOARD BOX WAS ONE METAL RECEPTACLE, ONE QUART IN CAPACITY. THE INNER METAL RECEPTACLES INTWO OF THE FIBERBOARD BOXES WERE LEAKING. ONE, THE INNER METAL FRICTION TYPE SEAL WAS NOT PROPERLY SEALED. THE OTHER ONE, THERE WAS NO ROOM FOR OUTAGE. ONE OF THE OTHER INNER METAL RECEPTACLES, THERE WAS A LARG INDENTATION IN THE SIDE.THE INNER ABSORBENT MATERIALS WAS FOAM RUBBER. THIS SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND PROPER CERTIFICATION DID ACCOMPANY IT. THIS SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGED DRUM AND FORWARDED ON TO IT'S DESTINATION.

SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZMAT (SSA/HM) A. ROQUET WAS NOTIFIED BY CAR FOREMAN, K. AMOS, THAT CAR GATX 94450 WAS FOUND LEAKING DURING A FRA INSPECTION. SSA/HM ROQUET RESPONDED AND INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE VALVES AND PLUGS WERE LOOSE.  THERE ALSO APPEARED TO BE A SLIGHT LEAK AT THE VALVE BASE.  ALL WERE TIGHTENED AND LEAK STOPPED.  CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR FURTHER MOVEMENT.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: SPECIAL AGENT/HAZMAT (SA/HM) S.D. WHITED WAS NOTIFIED THAT BULKTAINER UPUU 63008 WAS LEAKING WHEN RECEIVED AT THE CANAL STREET RAMP. SA/HM WHITED WAS OUT OF THE AREA AND SENIOR INSPECTOR DAN HEALY, BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES, RESPONDED.  INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE LEAK HAD OCCURRED FROM THE MANWAY COVER PLATE DUE TO ONE OF THE WING BOLTS ON THE COVER PLATE WHICH HAD NOT BEEN PROPERLY SECURED.  PRODUCT HAD SPILLED INTO THE OVER FLOW PAN AND DOWN THE DRAIN TUBES ONTO THE DECK OF THE FLATCAR.  INSPECTOR HEALY PROPERLY SECURED WING BOLTS WHICH STOPPED LEAK.  SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED IN THE SNOW ON THE FLATCAR.  INSPECTOR HEALY COLLECTED AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF PRODUCT.

MGR A. ROQUET WAS NOTIFIED THAT GATX 38625 WAS LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR. MGR ROQUET RESPONDED AND FOUND PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE LIQUID LINE FLANGE GASKET.  THE CAR PRESSURE WAS RELEASED BY THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE AND THE LIQUID LINE FLANGE AND LIQUID LINE PLUG WERE TIGHTENED WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK.  THE FRANGIBLE DISC IN THE SAFETY VENT WAS INSPECTED AND FOUND INTACT, HOWEVER, THE DISC WAS A BS&B, 100 PSI. THE DISC WAS REPLACED WITH THE BS&B, 60 PSI.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Piping or Fittings; Vapor Valve
column168: MGR D COOPER WAS NOTIFIED THAT ACFX 76904 WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR.  CAR WAS ISOLATED AND MGR. COOPER RESPONDED.  INSPECTION DETERMINED THE TOP PORTION OF THE TANK CAR ADJACENT TO THE SAFETY VALVE WAS COVERED WITH SOLUTION WHICH HAD SOLIFIED.  IT APPEARED THE SAFETY VALVE OPERATED DURING TRANSIT AS THE VALVE HAD RESET AND SHOWED NO SIGN OF BEING DEFECTIVE.  NO OTHER EXCEPTIONS WERE NOTED AND CAR WAS RELEASED FOR FURTHER MOVEMENT.  CHEMTREC, THE CA OFFICE OF EMERGENCY SERVICES,AND THE SAN BERNARDINO COUNTY DEPT OF ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH WERE ALL NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

MANAGER H.W. RODABOUGH WAS NOTIFIED THAT SWITCH CREWS SMELLED AMMONIA FROM GATX 30768. MANAGER RODABOUGH RESPONDED AND INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE PACKING FLANGE WAS TIGHTENED WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK. JIM LONG OF CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

MGR H.W.RODABOUGH WAS NOTIFIED THAT SWITCH CREW SMELLED AMMONIA FROM GATX 55561. MGR. RODABOUGH'S INSPECTION DETERMINED THE VAPOR VALVE WAS ONE QUARTER TURN OPEN AND THE PLUG WAS LOOSE.  ALSO, THE PACKING NUT ON THE STEM WAS LOOSE.  THE VALVE WAYS CLOSED, PLUG WAS TIGHTENED, AND THE PACKING NUT SECURED WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK. JIM COOPER OF CHETREC WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

AT APPROXIMATELY 0715 AM DOCKMAN OPENED TRAILER 17-3901 IN 4 DOOR AT CCM COLSOLIDATION DENTER, 106 NEW LOMBARD RD, CHICOPEE, MA.  THE DOCKMAN SMELLED A VERY STRONG ODOR AND INFORMED THE SUPERVISOR. THE AREA WAS CLEARED OF ALL EMPLOYEES AND THE TRAILER WAS TAKEN TO THE YARD FOR VENTILATION.  OFFICE MGR.  SAM MARTINI INVESTIGATED AND DISCOVERED LITER OF POISON B LEAKING SMALL AMOUNT, LIWUID WAS FROZEN TO THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER.  CHEMTREC AND THE SHIPPER WERE CALLED, ENVIRONMENTAL PRODUCTS AND SERVICE CAME TO THE CHICOPEE TERMINAL, CLEANED UP ALL LEAKING POISON B AND CLEAN UP PRODUCTS AND PLACED IN METAL OVERPACK DRUM WITH PLASTIC LINER FOR RETURN TO THE SHIPPER.  THE TRAILER WAS ALSO CLEANED AND PURGED AT THIS TIME.

CHECKER STRUCK DRUM WITH FORKLIFT CAUSING ALL CONTENTS OF THE DRUM TO LEAK OUT.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP BY REDDI ROOTER OF MEMPHIS.  THE OIL DRY WHICH ABSORBED THE SPILL WAS PLACED INTO 4 55 GALLON DRUMS.  THE DAMAGED FRUM WAS PLACED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AND ALL 5 DRUMS WERE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER PER LARRY BICKHAM OF ELF ATOCHEM ON PRO 331735110.  THE REMAINING 9 DRUMS WERE SENT ON TO CONSIGNEE.

WHILE CONDUCTING HAZMAT ROUTINE INSPECTIONS, MGR D. LOW NOTED TANK CAR NATX 50218 LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE MANWYA.  INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THREE SWING BOLTS ON THE MANWAY WERE ONLY FINGER TIGHT AND THE MANWAY GASKET WAS WORN.  GORE-TEX WAS APPLIED TO MANWAY AND THE SWING BOLTS WERE SECURED WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK.  JEFF BOTWINICK OF CHEMTREC AND JIM JUGLER OF LANMARK PERTROLEUM WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

column42: RECEPTACLES, SMALL, CONTAINING GAS OR GAS CARTRIDGES (FLAMMABLE) WITHOUT RELEASE DEVICE, NOT REFILLABLE AND NOT EXCEEDING 1 L CAPACITY
column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 0300 A UPRR SWITCH CREW FROM AVONDALE, LA WAS MAKING A PICK UP FORM THE ICG INTERCHANGE TRACK OFF THE NEW ORLEANS PUBLIC BELT RR IN METAIRIE, LA.  WHILE SHOVING 65 CARS, 6 OF THE CARS IN THE MIDDLE DERAILED.  THE DERAILED CARS INCLUDED THREE LOADED TAN CARS OF PROPYLENE. TWO OF THE PROPYLENE CARS REMAINED UPRIGHT WITH NO SIGNIFICANT DAMAGE, HOWEVER THE THIRD CAR, UTLX 910048, WENT OFF OF ITS TRUCKS AND ONTO ITS SIDE.  THE DERAILMENT AND SUBSEQUENT RERAILING OPERATION LEFT THE CAR WIHT BENT AND DAMAGED BODY BOLSTERS, DAMAGED RUNNING GEAR AND SAFETY APPLIANCES.  THE CAR COULD NOT SAFELY MOVE ONTO DESTINATION AND AS A RESULT THE LOAD WAS TRANSFERRED INTO UTLX 910056.  IT SHOULD BE NOTED THAT THERE WAS NO RELEASE OF COMMODITY FROM INCIDENT, HOWEVER, DURING RERAILING OPERATIONS, THE JEFFERSON PARISH SHERIFF'S OFFICE, IN CONJUNCTION WITH HAZMAT SPECIALIST, ADVISED RESIDENTS TO VOLUNTARILY EVACUATE THE AREA DURING RERAILING OF THE TANK CAR.

MGR D LOW WAS NOTIFIED THAT LIQUID WAS NOTIED LEAKING FROM THE LEFT SIDE COMPARTMENT OF ACFX 13206 IN CHEYENNE YARDS.  MGR LOW RESPONDED AND INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT LIQUID WAS COMING FROM DRAIN, LEFT SIDE COMPARTMENT.  INTACT SEAL KCS-N-644073 WAS REMOVED AND THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM THE LIQUID SAMPLE LINE.  THE GATE VALVE WAS SECURED WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK.  RIGHT SIDE COMPARTMENT HAD INTACT SEAL KCS-N-644075. RICH CIPOLLA OF PRAXAIR WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

SPECIAL AGENT/HAZMAT (SA/HM) J. JARA WAS NOTIFIED UTLX 90058 WAS RELEASING PRODUCT POSSIBLY THROUGH THE VENTING SYSTEM.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT. HAD BEEN NOTIFIED.  SA/HM JARA RESPONSDED AND A STEADY STREAM OF VAPOR WAS COMING FROM THE MANWAY AREA.  INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE GASKET AT THE MANWAY HAD FAILED NEAR THE LEFT SIDE OF THE DOME.  SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND MR. PAK OF CARDOX RESPONDED.  THE DECISION WAS  MADE TO TRANSFER PRODUCT.  CARDOX TANKER TRUCKS OFFLOADED UTLX 90058 CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

TRUCKS WERE STOPPED WAITING TO GET INTO DISPOSAL SITE WHEN SPILL WAS NOTICED.  TRUCKES WERE IMMEDIATLY MOVED TO CONTAINMENT AREA.  ROAD WAS SCRUBED DOWN AND LOSE SOIL WHICH WAS CONTAMINATED WAS IMMEDIATLY PICKED UP AND DRUMMED.  REMAINING LIQUID IN TRUCKS WAS REMOVED AND DRUMMED FOR DISPOSAL. NOTIFICATION TO STATE AND NRC WAS DONE BY SEAN MCDOUGALL WHO IS WITH ERTHCO A BROKER WE WERE HIRED BY TO TRANSPORT.  5 GALLONS OF LIQUID WAS ESTIMATED TO HAVE BEEN RELEASED, WHICH GENERATED 1 DRUM OF CONTAMINATED SOIL.  THIS MATERIAL AS WELL AS LIQUID ARE PENDING PROFILE APPROVAL AND WILL THEN BE STABILIZED AND LAND FILLED.

column168: DAN WHITING WAS LOADING FREIGHT INTO A TRAILER WHEN HIS FORKLIFT PUNCTURED THE DRUM.  THE DRUM COULD NOT BE RECOUPED AT DOCK.  THE TRAILER WAS PULLED TO AN ISOLATED AREA IN OUR YARD.  SOME OF THE CONTENTS OF THE DRUM LEAKED OUT OF THE TRAILER ONTO THE DIRT YARD.  CHEMTREC WAS THEN CALLED ON HOW TO DISPOSE OF THE CONTAMINATED DIRT.  ALL DOCKMENT WERE TOLD TO STAND PLYWOOD UP IN FRONT OF DRUMS AND WORK MORE CAREFULLY.

DOCKMAN, R QUIROGA, WAS UNLOADING FREIGHT FROM THE TOP OF THE DRUM OF HAZMAT.  HE INADVERTENTLY SPEARED THE DRUM WITH THE FORKLIFT BLADES, CAUSING SPILLAGE OF APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF THE NITROETHANE.  SPILL WAS CLEANED UP BY MR. QUIROGA.  SPEARED DRUM WAS PLACED IN OVERPACK DRUM AND AWAITING DISPOSTION.

CONRAIL TRAINMAN, F. W. ZEIGLER, REPORTED WHILE WALKING THROUGH THE  YARD BACK TO THE ENGINE HOUSE, HE WALKED THROUGH VAPOR EMITTING FROM TANK CAR GATX 20435 LOCATED ON TRACK 14. AN INSPECTION OF THE TANK CAR REVEALED A RUPTURED FRANGIBLE DISC IN THE SAFETY VENT HOUSING. THE DISC WAS REPLACED BY THE CONRAIL MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT AND THE CAR WAS FORWARDED TO DESTINATION. THE TRAINMAN WAS TAKEN TO HOLY SPIRIT HOSPITAL WHERE HE WAS TREATED AND RELEASED.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: SPECIAL AGENT/HAZMAT J JARA WAS NOTIFIED THAT ACFX 89103 WAS LEAKING IN THE STOCKTON YARD.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT. HAD BEEN NOTIFIED AND WAS RESPONDING.  SA/HM JARA RESPONDED AND INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS NOT SECURED.  PROTECTIVE SEAL GP DSP WA 35703246 WAS REMOVED AND BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS TIGHTENED A COMPLETE 360 DEGREE TURN WHICH STOPED THE LEAK.  THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WAS REMOVED AND VALVE WAS INSPECTED.  NO FURTHER EXCEPTIONS WERE NOTED.  JIM COOPER OF HCEMTREC AND TOM SPACY OF GEORGIA PACIFIC WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

WHILE CAR INSPECTORS WERE INSPECTING TRAIN IN TRACK 209 AT NORTH LITTLE ROCK, A STRONG ODOR OF GAS FROM CAR UTLX 99878 WAS NOTED.  MGR C L HILL WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT ICE WAS FORMING ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING.  INTERIOR INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT LIQUID PROPYLENE WAS SPRAYING FROM THE LIQUID VALVE AND ICE HAD FORMED AROUND THE VALVE.  VALVE WAS CLOSED AND VALVE PLUG WAS SECURED WRENCH TIGHT WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK. JOE MILAZZO OF CHEMTREC AND SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE LARRY LITTLE WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

column168: THE RELIEF FOREMAN ON DURTY 1-16-93, 0415 HOURS NOTIFIED DIVISION MECHANICAL OFFICER MR. GAYLON OVERTON THAT TANK CAR SAUX 708 HAD BEEN REPORTED BY A SWITCH CREW AT THE DR&W NORTH YARD FACILITY TO HAVE A PROPANE ODOR OR LEAK.  MR. OVERTON EXAMINED THE CAR AND FOUND AN ACCUMULATION OF ICE UNDER THE DOME LID ON TOP OF THE CAR.  HE ALSO COULD DETECT THE FAINT ODOR OF PROPANE.  HE CHIPPED THE ICE AWAY, AND FOUND A PLUG IN THE LIQUID LINE VALVE HAD BECOME LOOSE.  HE TIGHTENED THE PLUG AND RETURNED THE CAR TO SERVICE.

BUCKET WAS FOUND IN UNLOAD AT 1840 HRS.  CARDBOARD BAG FOUND IT WAS WET UPON INSPECTION I SAW THAT THERE WAS A BAD SEAL ON BUCKET - I RESEALED THE LID ON BUCKET & RETURNED TO SHIPPER.  I USED THE MALLINCKRODT METHOD TO DISPOSE OF CONTAMINATED CARDBOARD.

SCOTT RODMAN WAS THE RESPONDER AND TOOK ACTION TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS, BAGGED THE PACKAGE AND BROUGHT TO THE CAGE.
